Yes, that became apparent when I came to code the comparison routine. :) 
 Yeh, like NEAT I use an &#39;innovation&#39; number on each node of the tree.

Preliminary results don&#39;t show any significant benefit from speciation, 
however I have identified a possible reason why and I have some avenues 
of investigation to follow up. Basically on close inspection of the 
trees I can see a large number of redundant(neutral) nodes. Allowing 
neutral nodes to leak in effectively means that the fitness search space 
is not closely coupled to the compatibility space. Two genomes that 
describe the same network can have wildly different tree structures due 
to large numbers of neutral nodes and are therefore deemed incompatible.

My evaluation function already goes some way to tackle this problem by 
reducing the fitness scores with a punishment factor. This is basically 
a weighted combination of genome size, decoded network size (complexity 
actually, since I factor in connections) and CPU decode time. However it 
seems the punishment is not strong enough to keep the neutral nodes from 
proliferating.  However if I increase the punishment too much I am 
afraid of stifling innovation.

Perhaps one solution is to use a stepped punishment function. E.g. 
instead of:

punishment = numberOfNodes / 3.0;
  use
punishment = floor(numberOfNodes / 3.0);

Using this function allows genomes to more freely explore the search 
space in jumps of 3 nodes. When they reach 4, 7, 10 etc. they are 
suddenly punished and have a big step to overcome (which is bad). In 
experiments this approach definitely improved search times, but I feel 
the the stepping may come back to bite me.

Out of curiousity does anyone know if NEAT has been applied to the prey 
capture problem? This is the only environment I have available to-date 
for comparison with other systems.

